This procedure is the Top Trading Cycles mechanism (students point to a school; each school points to its highest-priority remaining student; any cycle is finalized). To see if misreporting can improve my outcome, check the cycle structure given others’ fixed first choices. Initially A->E, B->E, C->D, D(me)->E, E->C. Schools point: E->E, C->B, D->A, A->B, B->A. There is an immediate 1-cycle E<->E, so Student_E is removed with School_C (their application) and School_E (its seat) filled. With School_E gone, remaining students apply to their best remaining: A->B, B->D, C->D, D->A. Schools point among remaining: A->B, B->A, D->A. This creates a cycle A<->B, so Student_A gets School_B and Student_B gets School_D. Then C and I remain; I apply to School_A, C applies to School_D (full) then School_C (full) then School_A, and School_A points to me, forming D<->A so I get School_A. Since School_E is unattainable (it is always taken immediately by Student_E via the E<->E cycle regardless of my report) and I already obtain my best feasible option (School_A), any deviation cannot improve upon School_A; therefore I should submit my true order.
